\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
7.14.14
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
3.18.

\series default
 Given below is the proof of a result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proof 
\series default
Assume that n is an odd integer.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2k+1$
\end_inset

 for some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $3n-5=3\left(2k+1\right)-5=6k+3-5=6k-2=2\left(3k-1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 3k − 1 is an integer, 3n − 5 is even.
 Which of the following is proved above?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) 3n−5is an even integer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2) If n is an odd integer, then 3n − 5 is an even integer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3) Let n be an integer.
 If 3n − 5 is an even integer, then n is an odd integer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(4) Let n be an integer.
 If 3n − 5 is an odd integer, then n is an even integer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Answer
\series default
 The correct answers are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(4\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The given proof is a direct proof
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 and a proof by contrapositive of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(4\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
3.19.

\series default
 Evaluate the proposed proof of the following result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Result
\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are integers of the same parity, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x-y$
\end_inset

 is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proof 
\series default
Let x and y be two integers of the same parity.
 We consider two cases, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
according to whether x and y are both even or are both odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Case 1.
 x and y are both even.
 Let x = 6 and y = 2, which are both even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then x − y = 4, which is even.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Case 2.
 x and y are both odd.
 Let x = 7 and y = 1, which are both odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then x − y = 6, which is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proof Eval
\series default
 
\end_layout

